The scandal regarding recently released text messages indicates that deep inside Boeing problems had been found and not addressed. There are two problems for Boeing, and for the FAA. There is the technical work of demonstrating that the fix to the MCAS system has been thoroughly verified. The second problem is public acceptance of the plane. Boeing's official stance is that the plane will be ready to fly before the end of 2019. But will the public be ready to get on the plane? I don't think so.
I am adjusting my prior forecast to reflect a higher probability for this matter to extend later into 2020.
The longer it has taken to get regulatory approval, the more Boeing related issues that are discovered along the way. This approval may take another 6 months to obtain.

I have halved the probability of a commercial flight of the 737 MAX before the end of the year. This is partly in view of the latest news about the texts of the test pilots[1] and that simulated flights will only begin in early November [2], which makes it unlikely (if not impossible) to have commercial flights till January.

Well, besides the points considered previously, there is the point that though the FAA could decide to give the green light to the 737 Max before other agencies, such as EASA and CAAC, that would be a bad move regarding the public. Though the requirements for civil aviation are more stringent in the US (particularly pilots' required experience), this is not necessarily the case for aviation outside of the US (particularly in growing markets). Yet this is not necessarily known (or internalized) by the average person taking a flight, which means that the FAA might decide to err on the safe side.

From the Economist - summarizing WSJ article “ The Wall Street Journal reported that Boeing’s engineers had omitted important safeguards in software linked to fatal crashes of two 737 MAX airliners that killed 346 people. The newspaper said the safeguards had been included in an earlier version of the flight-control system installed on a military tanker aircraft. America’s Department of Justice has previously launched a criminal investigation into the design and certification of the aircraft.”

As of 9/11/19, Boeing "still" targeting "early fourth quarter" for a return to service of the 737 Max. Of regulatory bodies responsible for certifying the 737 Max, the FAA appears to be working very closely with Boeing and over the course of the investigation has generally seemed to lay a large portion of the blame on undertrained pilots vs. structural safety issues associated with the 737 Max. Since the question specifically is for a U.S. commercial flight, I see no reason why the company's estimate should not be the best estimate of reality. I assign 15% probability that this occurs after 1/1/2020 due to potential Boeing management overconfidence and the possibility for tail outcomes delaying the return of the aircraft to commercial service.

The Joint Authorities Technical Review - a precursor, apparently, to any final FAA consideration to resume flying, has 9 safety experts worldwide, in addition to participants from FAA and NASA. It is chaired by the former head of the NTSB. It announced on Aug 30 that it is taking "additional time" to finish documenting its work. "Additional" time? That rules out return to flight by end of September. Subsequently, on Sep 6, the new 777X failed a stress test on the wings - as a rear door blew out and the cabin depressurized. An further impediment, perhaps, to a demonstration of engineering and manufacturing excellence? That puts the chance of a hasty reintroduction in the "low" category.

White knuckle time: American Airlines says it may have to cancel up to 140 flights a day from November to early December, as it follows United Airlines in pulling the Boeing 737 MAX 8 from its schedule.
